# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: response-reactions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] In physical chemistry and chemical engineering, **extent of reaction** is a quantity that measures the extent to which the reaction has proceeded.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] Often, it refers specifically to the value of the extent of reaction when equilibrium has been reached.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] It is usually denoted by the Greek letter ξ.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] The extent of reaction is usually defined so that it has units of amount (moles).
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] It was introduced by the Belgian scientist Théophile de Donder.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] Suppose an infinitesimal amount $dn_{i}$ of the reactant A changes into B and C.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] This requires that all three mole numbers change according to the stoichiometry of the reaction, but they will not change by the same amounts.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] However, the extent of reaction $\xi$ can be used to describe the changes on a common footing as needed.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] The change of the number of moles of A can be represented by the equation $dn_{A}=-d\xi$ , the change of B is $dn_{B}=+2d\xi$ , and the change of C is $dn_{C}=+3d\xi$ .
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] where $n_{i}$ denotes the number of moles of the $i^{th}$ reactant or product and $\nu _{i}$ is the *stoichiometric number* of the $i^{th}$ reactant or product.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] Although less common, we see from this expression that since the stoichiometric number can either be considered to be dimensionless or to have units of moles, conversely the extent of reaction can either be considered to have units of moles or to be a unitless mole fraction.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] The extent of reaction represents the amount of progress made towards equilibrium in a chemical reaction.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] The extent of a reaction is generally defined as zero at the beginning of the reaction.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] Thus the change of $\xi$ is the extent itself.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] Although in the example above the extent of reaction was positive since the system shifted in the forward direction, this usage implies that in general the extent of reaction can be positive or negative, depending on the direction that the system shifts from its initial composition.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] The relation between the change in Gibbs reaction energy and Gibbs energy can be defined as the slope of the Gibbs energy plotted against the extent of reaction at constant pressure and temperature.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] This formula leads to the Nernst equation when applied to the oxidation-reduction reaction which generates the voltage of a voltaic cell.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] Analogously, the relation between the change in reaction enthalpy and enthalpy can be defined.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] The extent of reaction is a useful quantity in computations with equilibrium reactions.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] In the above, we note that the stoichiometric number of a reactant is negative.
[src:response-reactions/extent-of-reaction] Now when we know the extent, we can rearrange the equation and calculate the equilibrium amounts of B and C.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] In mathematics, the **Hessian matrix**, **Hessian** or (less commonly) **Hesse matrix** is a square matrix of second-order partial derivatives of a scalar-valued function, or scalar field.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] It describes the local curvature of a function of many variables.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The Hessian matrix was developed in the 19th century by the German mathematician Ludwig Otto Hesse and later named after him.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] Hesse originally used the term "functional determinants".
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The Hessian is sometimes denoted by H or $\nabla \nabla$ or $\nabla ^{2}$ or $\nabla \otimes \nabla$ or $D^{2}$ .
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If furthermore the second partial derivatives are all continuous, the Hessian matrix is a symmetric matrix by the symmetry of second derivatives.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The determinant of the Hessian matrix is called the *Hessian determinant*.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If f is a homogeneous polynomial in three variables, the equation $f=0$ is the implicit equation of a plane projective curve.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The inflection points of the curve are exactly the non-singular points where the Hessian determinant is zero.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] It follows by Bézout's theorem that a cubic plane curve has at most 9 inflection points, since the Hessian determinant is a polynomial of degree 3.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The Hessian matrix of a convex function is positive semi-definite.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] This implies that at a local minimum the Hessian is positive-semidefinite, and at a local maximum the Hessian is negative-semidefinite.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] For positive-semidefinite and negative-semidefinite Hessians, the test is inconclusive (a critical point where the Hessian is semidefinite but not definite may be a local extremum or a saddle point).
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] However, more can be said from the point of view of Morse theory.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The second-derivative test for functions of one and two variables is simpler than the general case.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] In one variable, the Hessian contains exactly one second derivative; if it is positive, then x is a local minimum, and if it is negative, then x is a local maximum; if it is zero, then the test is inconclusive.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] In two variables, the determinant can be used, because the determinant is the product of the eigenvalues.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If it is positive, then the eigenvalues are both positive or both negative.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If it is negative, then the two eigenvalues have different signs.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If it is zero, then the second-derivative test is inconclusive.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] Specifically, the sufficient condition for a minimum is that all of these principal minors be positive, while the sufficient condition for a maximum is that the minors alternate in sign, with the $1\times 1$ minor being negative.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If the gradient (the vector of the partial derivatives) of a function f is zero at some point $\mathbf {x} ,$ then f has a *critical point* (or *stationary point*) at $\mathbf {x} .$ The determinant of the Hessian at $\mathbf {x}$ is called, in some contexts, a discriminant.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The Hessian matrix plays an important role in Morse theory and catastrophe theory, because its kernel and eigenvalues allow classification of the critical points.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The determinant of the Hessian matrix, when evaluated at a critical point of a function, is equal to the Gaussian curvature of the function considered as a manifold.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The eigenvalues of the Hessian at that point are the principal curvatures of the function, and the eigenvectors are the principal directions of curvature.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] Hessian matrices are used in large-scale optimization problems within Newton-type methods because they are the coefficient of the quadratic term of a local Taylor expansion of a function.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] For such situations, truncated-Newton and quasi-Newton algorithms have been developed.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The latter family of algorithms use approximations to the Hessian; one of the most popular quasi-Newton algorithms is BFGS.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] Notably regarding Randomized Search Heuristics, the evolution strategy's covariance matrix adapts to the inverse of the Hessian matrix, up to a scalar factor and small random fluctuations.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] This result has been formally proven for a single-parent strategy and a static model, as the population size increases, relying on the quadratic approximation.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The Hessian matrix is commonly used for expressing image processing operators in image processing and computer vision (see the Laplacian of Gaussian (LoG) blob detector, the determinant of Hessian (DoH) blob detector and scale space).
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] It can be used in normal mode analysis to calculate the different molecular frequencies in infrared spectroscopy.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] It can also be used in local sensitivity and statistical diagnostics.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] A ***bordered Hessian*** is used for the second-derivative test in certain constrained optimization problems.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If there are, say, m constraints then the zero in the upper-left corner is an $m\times m$ block of zeros, and there are m border rows at the top and m border columns at the left.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] The second derivative test consists here of sign restrictions of the determinants of a certain set of $n-m$ submatrices of the bordered Hessian.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] Intuitively, the m constraints can be thought of as reducing the problem to one with $n-m$ free variables.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] There are thus $n-m$ minors to consider, each evaluated at the specific point being considered as a candidate maximum or minimum.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] If f is instead a vector field $\mathbf {f$ that is, $\mathbf {f} (\mathbf {x} )=\left(f_{1}(\mathbf {x} ),f_{2}(\mathbf {x} ),\ldots ,f_{m}(\mathbf {x} )\right),$ then the collection of second partial derivatives is not a $n\times n$ matrix, but rather a third-order tensor.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] In the context of several complex variables, the Hessian may be generalized.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] As the object of study in several complex variables are holomorphic functions, that is, solutions to the n-dimensional Cauchy–Riemann conditions, we usually look on the part of the Hessian that contains information invariant under holomorphic changes of coordinates.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] Let $(M,g)$ be a Riemannian manifold and $\nabla$ its Levi-Civita connection.
[src:response-reactions/hessian-determinant] Let $f:M\to \mathbb {R}$ be a smooth function.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1863, Yale University awarded Gibbs the first American doctorate in engineering.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] After a three-year sojourn in Europe, Gibbs spent the rest of his career at Yale, where he was a professor of mathematical physics from 1871 until his death in 1903.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Working in relative isolation, he became the earliest theoretical scientist in the United States to earn an international reputation and was praised by Albert Einstein as "the greatest mind in American history".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1901, Gibbs received what was then considered the highest honor awarded by the international scientific community, the Copley Medal of the Royal Society of London, "for his contributions to mathematical physics".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Commentators and biographers have remarked on the contrast between Gibbs's quiet, solitary life in turn of the century New England and the great international impact of his ideas.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Though his work was almost entirely theoretical, the practical value of Gibbs's contributions became evident with the development of industrial chemistry during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Millikan, in pure science, Gibbs "did for statistical mechanics and thermodynamics what Laplace did for celestial mechanics and Maxwell did for electrodynamics, namely, made his field a well-nigh finished theoretical structure".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs was born in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He belonged to an old Yankee family that had produced distinguished American clergymen and academics since the 17th century.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He was the fourth of five children and the only son of Josiah Willard Gibbs Sr. and his wife Mary Anna, *née* Van Cleve.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] On his father's side, he was descended from Samuel Willard, who served as acting President of Harvard College from 1701 to 1707.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] On his mother's side, one of his ancestors was the Rev.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Jonathan Dickinson, the first president of the College of New Jersey (later Princeton University).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's given name, which he shared with his father and several other members of his extended family, derived from his ancestor Josiah Willard, who had been Secretary of the Province of Massachusetts Bay in the 18th century.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] His paternal grandmother, Mercy (Prescott) Gibbs, was the sister of Rebecca Minot Prescott Sherman, the wife of American founding father Roger Sherman; and he was the second cousin of Roger Sherman Baldwin (see the Amistad case below).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The elder Gibbs was generally known to his family and colleagues as "Josiah", while the son was called "Willard".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Josiah Gibbs was a linguist and theologian who served as professor of sacred literature at Yale Divinity School from 1824 until his death in 1861.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He is chiefly remembered today as the abolitionist who found an interpreter for the African passengers of the ship *Amistad*, allowing them to testify during the trial that followed their rebellion against being sold as slaves.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Willard Gibbs was educated at the Hopkins School and entered Yale College in 1854 at the age of 15.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] At Yale, Gibbs received prizes for excellence in mathematics and Latin, and he graduated in 1858, near the top of his class.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He remained at Yale as a graduate student at the Sheffield Scientific School.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] At age 19, soon after his graduation from college, Gibbs was inducted into the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, a scholarly institution composed primarily of members of the Yale faculty.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Relatively few documents from the period survive and it is difficult to reconstruct the details of Gibbs's early career with precision.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In the opinion of biographers, Gibbs's principal mentor and champion, both at Yale and in the Connecticut Academy, was probably the astronomer and mathematician Hubert Anson Newton, a leading authority on meteors, who remained Gibbs's lifelong friend and confidant.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] After the death of his father in 1861, Gibbs inherited enough money to make him financially independent.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Recurrent pulmonary trouble ailed the young Gibbs and his physicians were concerned that he might be susceptible to tuberculosis, which had killed his mother.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He also suffered from astigmatism, whose treatment was then still largely unfamiliar to oculists, so that Gibbs had to diagnose himself and grind his own lenses.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Though in later years he used glasses only for reading or other close work, Gibbs's delicate health and imperfect eyesight probably explain why he did not volunteer to fight in the Civil War of 1861–65.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He was not conscripted and he remained at Yale for the duration of the war.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1863, Gibbs received the first Doctorate of Philosophy (PhD) in engineering granted in the US, for a thesis entitled "On the Form of the Teeth of Wheels in Spur Gearing", in which he used geometrical techniques to investigate the optimum design for gears.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1861, Yale had become the first US university to offer a PhD degree and Gibbs's was only the fifth PhD granted in the US in any subject.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] After graduation, Gibbs was appointed as tutor at the college for a term of three years.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] During the first two years, he taught Latin, and during the third year, he taught "natural philosophy" (i.e., physics).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1866, he patented a design for a railway brake and read a paper before the Connecticut Academy, entitled "The Proper Magnitude of the Units of Length", in which he proposed a scheme for rationalizing the system of units of measurement used in mechanics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] After his term as tutor ended, Gibbs traveled to Europe with his sisters.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] They spent the winter of 1866–67 in Paris, where Gibbs attended lectures at the Sorbonne and the Collège de France, given by such distinguished mathematical scientists as Joseph Liouville and Michel Chasles.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Having undertaken a punishing regimen of study, Gibbs caught a serious cold and a doctor, fearing tuberculosis, advised him to rest on the Riviera, where he and his sisters spent several months and where he made a full recovery.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Moving to Berlin, Gibbs attended the lectures taught by mathematicians Karl Weierstrass and Leopold Kronecker, as well as by chemist Heinrich Gustav Magnus.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In August 1867, Gibbs's sister Julia was married in Berlin to Addison Van Name, who had been Gibbs's classmate at Yale.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The newly married couple returned to New Haven, leaving Gibbs and his sister Anna in Germany.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In Heidelberg, Gibbs was exposed to the work of physicists Gustav Kirchhoff and Hermann von Helmholtz, and chemist Robert Bunsen.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] At the time, German academics were the leading authorities in the natural sciences, especially chemistry and thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs returned to Yale in June 1869 and briefly taught French to engineering students.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] It was probably also around this time that he worked on a new design for a steam-engine governor, his last significant investigation in mechanical engineering.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1871, he was appointed Professor of Mathematical Physics at Yale, the first such professorship in the United States.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs, who had independent means and had yet to publish anything, was assigned to teach graduate students exclusively and was hired without salary.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] His papers on the geometric representation of thermodynamic quantities appeared in the *Transactions of the Connecticut Academy*.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Although the journal had few readers capable of understanding Gibbs's work, he shared reprints with correspondents in Europe and received an enthusiastic response from James Clerk Maxwell at Cambridge.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Maxwell even made, with his own hands, a clay model illustrating Gibbs's construct.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He then produced two plaster casts of his model and mailed one to Gibbs.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] That cast is on display at the Yale physics department.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Maxwell included a chapter on Gibbs's work in the next edition of his *Theory of Heat*, published in 1875.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He explained the usefulness of Gibbs's graphical methods in a lecture to the Chemical Society of London and even referred to it in the article on "Diagrams" that he wrote for the *Encyclopædia Britannica*.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Prospects of collaboration between him and Gibbs were cut short by Maxwell's early death in 1879, aged 48.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The joke later circulated in New Haven that "only one man lived who could understand Gibbs's papers.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs then extended his thermodynamic analysis to multi-phase chemical systems (i.e., to systems composed of more than one form of matter) and considered a variety of concrete applications.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He described that research in a monograph titled "On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances", published by the Connecticut Academy in two parts that appeared respectively in 1875 and 1878.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] That work, which covers about three hundred pages and contains exactly seven hundred numbered mathematical equations, begins with a quotation from Rudolf Clausius that expresses what would later be called the first and second laws of thermodynamics: "The energy of the world is constant.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's monograph rigorously and ingeniously applied his thermodynamic techniques to the interpretation of physico-chemical phenomena, explaining and relating what had previously been a mass of isolated facts and observations.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The work has been described as "the *Principia* of thermodynamics" and as a work of "practically unlimited scope".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] It solidly laid the foundation for physical Chemistry.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Wilhelm Ostwald, who translated Gibbs's monograph into German, referred to Gibbs as the "founder of chemical energetics".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs continued to work without pay until 1880, when the new Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore, Maryland offered him a position paying $3,000 per year.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In response, Yale offered him an annual salary of $2,000, which he was content to accept.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1879, Gibbs derived the Gibbs–Appell equation of motion, rediscovered in 1900 by Paul Émile Appell.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] From 1880 to 1884, Gibbs worked on developing the exterior algebra of Hermann Grassmann into a vector calculus well-suited to the needs of physicists.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] With this object in mind, Gibbs distinguished between the dot and cross products of two vectors and introduced the concept of dyadics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Similar work was carried out independently, and at around the same time, by the British mathematical physicist and engineer Oliver Heaviside.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs sought to convince other physicists of the convenience of the vectorial approach over the quaternionic calculus of William Rowan Hamilton, which was then widely used by British scientists.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] This led him, in the early 1890s, to a controversy with Peter Guthrie Tait and others in the pages of *Nature*.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's lecture notes on vector calculus were privately printed in 1881 and 1884 for the use of his students, and were later adapted by Edwin Bidwell Wilson into a textbook, *Vector Analysis*, published in 1901.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] That book helped to popularize the "del" notation that is widely used today in electrodynamics and fluid mechanics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In other mathematical work, he re-discovered the "Gibbs phenomenon" in the theory of Fourier series (which, unbeknownst to him and to later scholars, had been described fifty years before by an obscure English mathematician, Henry Wilbraham).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] From 1882 to 1889, Gibbs wrote five papers on physical optics, in which he investigated birefringence and other optical phenomena and defended Maxwell's electromagnetic theory of light against the mechanical theories of Lord Kelvin and others.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In his work on optics, just as much as in his work on thermodynamics, Gibbs deliberately avoided speculating about the microscopic structure of matter and purposefully confined his research problems to those that can be solved from broad general principles and experimentally confirmed facts.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The methods that he used were highly original and the obtained results showed decisively the correctness of Maxwell's electromagnetic theory.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs coined the term *statistical mechanics* and introduced key concepts in the corresponding mathematical description of physical systems, including the notions of chemical potential (1876) and statistical ensemble (1902).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's derivation of the laws of thermodynamics from the statistical properties of systems consisting of many particles was presented in his highly influential textbook *Elementary Principles in Statistical Mechanics*, published in 1902, a year before his death.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's retiring personality and intense focus on his work limited his accessibility to students.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] His principal protégé was Edwin Bidwell Wilson, who nonetheless explained that "except in the classroom I saw very little of Gibbs.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] After Gibbs's death, Fisher financed the publication of his *Collected Works*.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Another distinguished student was Lee De Forest, later a pioneer of radio technology.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs died in New Haven on April 28, 1903, at the age of 64, the victim of an acute intestinal obstruction.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] A funeral was conducted two days later at his home on 121 High Street, and his body was buried in the nearby Grove Street Cemetery.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In May, Yale organized a memorial meeting at the Sloane Laboratory.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Thomson was in attendance and delivered a brief address.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs never married, living all his life in his childhood home with his sister Julia and her husband Addison Van Name, who was the Yale librarian.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Except for his customary summer vacations in the Adirondacks (at Keene Valley, New York) and later at the White Mountains (in Intervale, New Hampshire), his sojourn in Europe in 1866–1869 was almost the only time that Gibbs spent outside New Haven.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He joined Yale's College Church (a Congregational church) at the end of his freshman year and remained a regular attendant for the rest of his life.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs generally voted for the Republican candidate in presidential elections but, like other "Mugwumps", his concern over the growing corruption associated with machine politics led him to support Grover Cleveland, a conservative Democrat, in the election of 1884.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Little else is known of his religious or political views, which he mostly kept to himself.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs did not produce a substantial personal correspondence, and many of his letters were later lost or destroyed.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Beyond the technical writings concerning his research, he published only two other pieces: a brief obituary for Rudolf Clausius, one of the founders of the mathematical theory of thermodynamics, and a longer biographical memoir of his mentor at Yale, H.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He was a careful investor and financial manager, and at his death in 1903 his estate was valued at $100,000 (roughly $3.58 million today).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] For many years, he served as trustee, secretary, and treasurer of his alma mater, the Hopkins School.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Arthur appointed him as one of the commissioners to the National Conference of Electricians, which convened in Philadelphia in September 1884, and Gibbs presided over one of its sessions.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] A keen and skilled horseman, Gibbs was seen habitually in New Haven driving his sister's carriage.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In an obituary published in the *American Journal of Science*, Gibbs's former student Henry A.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's papers from the 1870s introduced the idea of expressing the internal energy *U* of a system in terms of the entropy *S*, in addition to the usual state variables of volume *V*, pressure *p*, and temperature *T*.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He also introduced the concept of the chemical potential $\mu$ of a given chemical species, defined to be the rate of the increase in *U* associated with the increase in the number *N* of molecules of that species (at constant entropy and volume).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] where *T* is the absolute temperature, *p* is the pressure, d*S* is an infinitesimal change in entropy and d*V* is an infinitesimal change of volume.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The last term is the sum, over all the chemical species in a chemical reaction, of the chemical potential, *μ*i, of the *i*-th species, multiplied by the infinitesimal change in the number of moles, d*N*i of that species.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] When the Gibbs free energy for a chemical reaction is negative, the reaction will proceed spontaneously.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] When a chemical system is at equilibrium, the change in Gibbs free energy is zero.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs also obtained what later came to be known as the "Gibbs–Duhem equation".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The publication of the paper "On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances" (1874–1878) is now regarded as a landmark in the development of chemistry.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In it, Gibbs developed a rigorous mathematical theory for various transport phenomena, including adsorption, electrochemistry, and the Marangoni effect in fluid mixtures.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] for the number *F* of variables that may be independently controlled in an equilibrium mixture of *C* components existing in *P* phases.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The phase rule is very useful in diverse areas, such as metallurgy, mineralogy, and petrology.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] It can also be applied to various research problems in physical chemistry.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He introduced the concept of "phase of a mechanical system".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He used the concept to define the microcanonical, canonical, and grand canonical ensembles; all related to the Gibbs measure, thus obtaining a more general formulation of the statistical properties of many-particle systems than Maxwell and Boltzmann had achieved before him.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] where $k_{\text{B}}$ is the Boltzmann constant, while the sum is over all possible microstates i , with $p_{i}$ the corresponding probability of the microstate (see Gibbs entropy formula).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] This same formula would later play a central role in Claude Shannon's information theory and is therefore often seen as the basis of the modern information-theoretical interpretation of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's analysis of irreversibility, and his formulation of Boltzmann's H-theorem and of the ergodic hypothesis, were major influences on the mathematical physics of the 20th century.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] His resolution of the so-called "Gibbs paradox", about the entropy of the mixing of gases, is now often cited as a prefiguration of the indistinguishability of particles required by quantum physics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] British scientists, including Maxwell, had relied on Hamilton's quaternions in order to express the dynamics of physical quantities, like the electric and magnetic fields, having both a magnitude and a direction in three-dimensional space.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In his Yale classroom notes he defined two distinct types of products for a pair of vectors: a dot product (or scalar product) and a cross product (or vector product).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He also introduced the now common notation for them.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Through the 1901 textbook *Vector Analysis* prepared by E.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Wilson from Gibbs notes, he was largely responsible for the development of the vector calculus techniques still used today in electrodynamics and fluid mechanics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] While he was working on vector analysis in the late 1870s, Gibbs discovered that his approach was similar to the one that Grassmann had taken in his "multiple algebra".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs then sought to publicize Grassmann's work, stressing that it was both more general and historically prior to Hamilton's quaternionic algebra.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] As Gibbs had advocated in the 1880s and 1890s, quaternions were eventually all but abandoned by physicists in favor of the vectorial approach developed by him and, independently, by Oliver Heaviside.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs applied his vector methods to the determination of planetary and comet orbits.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He also developed the concept of mutually reciprocal triads of vectors that later proved to be of importance in crystallography.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Though Gibbs's research on physical optics is less well known today than his other work, it made a significant contribution to classical electromagnetism by applying Maxwell's equations to the theory of optical processes such as birefringence, dispersion, and optical activity.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In that work, Gibbs showed that those processes could be accounted for by Maxwell's equations without any special assumptions about the microscopic structure of matter or about the nature of the medium in which electromagnetic waves were supposed to propagate (the so-called luminiferous ether).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Shortly afterwards, the electromagnetic nature of light was demonstrated by the experiments of Heinrich Hertz in Germany.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs worked at a time when there was little tradition of rigorous theoretical science in the United States.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] His research was not easily understandable to his students or his colleagues, and he made no effort to popularize his ideas or to simplify their exposition to make them more accessible.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] His seminal work on thermodynamics was published mostly in the *Transactions of the Connecticut Academy*, a journal edited by his librarian brother-in-law, which was little read in the US and even less so in Europe.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] When Gibbs submitted his long paper on the equilibrium of heterogeneous substances to the academy, both Elias Loomis and H.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Newton protested that they did not understand Gibbs's work at all, but they helped to raise the money needed to pay for the typesetting of the many mathematical symbols in the paper.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Several Yale faculty members, as well as business and professional men in New Haven, contributed funds for that purpose.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Even though it had been immediately embraced by Maxwell, Gibbs's graphical formulation of the laws of thermodynamics came into widespread use only in the mid 20th century, with the work of László Tisza and Herbert Callen.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] On the other hand, Gibbs did receive the major honors then possible for an academic scientist in the US.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1879 and received the 1880 Rumford Prize from the American Academy of Arts and Sciences for his work on chemical thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1895, he was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1895.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He was also awarded honorary doctorates by Princeton University and Williams College.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In Europe, Gibbs was inducted as honorary member of the London Mathematical Society in 1892 and elected Foreign Member of the Royal Society in 1897.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He was elected as corresponding member of the Prussian and French Academies of Science and received honorary doctorates from the universities of Dublin, Erlangen, and Christiania (now Oslo).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] From this, Rota concluded that Gibbs's work was better known among the scientific elite of his day than the published material suggests.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Lynde Wheeler reproduces that mailing list in an appendix to his biography of Gibbs.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's most immediate and obvious influence was on physical chemistry and statistical mechanics, two disciplines which he greatly helped to found.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] During Gibbs's lifetime, his phase rule was experimentally validated by Dutch chemist H.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Bakhuis Roozeboom, who showed how to apply it in a variety of situations, thereby assuring it of widespread use.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In industrial chemistry, Gibbs's thermodynamics found many applications during the early 20th century, from electrochemistry to the development of the Haber process for the synthesis of ammonia.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] D. van der Waals received the 1910 Nobel Prize "for his work on the equation of state for gases and liquids" he acknowledged the great influence of Gibbs's work on that subject.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Max Planck received the 1918 Nobel Prize for his work on quantum mechanics, particularly his 1900 paper on Planck's law for quantized black-body radiation.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] That work was based largely on the thermodynamics of Kirchhoff, Boltzmann, and Gibbs.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Lewis and Merle Randall, and *Modern Thermodynamics by the Methods of Willard Gibbs* (1933), by Edward A.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's work on statistical ensembles, as presented in his 1902 textbook, has had a great impact in both theoretical physics and in pure mathematics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Initially unaware of Gibbs's contributions in that field, Albert Einstein wrote three papers on statistical mechanics, published between 1902 and 1904.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] After reading Gibbs's textbook (which was translated into German by Ernst Zermelo in 1905), Einstein declared that Gibbs's treatment was superior to his own and explained that he would not have written those papers if he had known Gibbs's work.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's early papers on the use of graphical methods in thermodynamics reflect a powerfully original understanding of what mathematicians would later call "convex analysis", including ideas that, according to Barry Simon, "lay dormant for about seventy-five years".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Important mathematical concepts based on Gibbs's work on thermodynamics and statistical mechanics include the Gibbs lemma in game theory, the Gibbs inequality in information theory, as well as Gibbs sampling in computational statistics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The development of vector calculus was Gibbs's other great contribution to mathematics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Wilson's textbook *Vector Analysis*, based on Gibbs's lectures at Yale, did much to propagate the use of vectorial methods and notation in both mathematics and theoretical physics, definitively displacing the quaternions that had until then been dominant in the scientific literature.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] At Yale, Gibbs was also mentor to Lee De Forest, who went on to invent the triode amplifier and has been called the "father of radio".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs also had an indirect influence on mathematical economics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] He supervised the thesis of Irving Fisher, who received the first PhD in economics from Yale in 1891.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In that work, published in 1892 as *Mathematical Investigations in the Theory of Value and Prices*, Fisher drew a direct analogy between Gibbsian equilibrium in physical and chemical systems, and the general equilibrium of markets, and he used Gibbs's vectorial notation.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's protégé Edwin Bidwell Wilson became, in turn, a mentor to leading American economist and Nobel Laureate Paul Samuelson.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Mathematician Norbert Wiener cited Gibbs's use of probability in the formulation of statistical mechanics as "the first great revolution of twentieth century physics" and as a major influence on his conception of cybernetics.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] When the German physical chemist Walther Nernst visited Yale in 1906 to give the Silliman lecture, he was surprised to find no tangible memorial for Gibbs.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Nernst donated his $500 lecture fee to the university to help pay for a suitable monument.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] This was finally unveiled in 1912, in the form of a bronze bas-relief by sculptor Lee Lawrie, installed in the Sloane Physics Laboratory.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1910, the American Chemical Society established the Willard Gibbs Award for eminent work in pure or applied chemistry.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1923, the American Mathematical Society endowed the Josiah Willard Gibbs Lectureship, "to show the public some idea of the aspects of mathematics and its applications".
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Willard Gibbs Professorship in Theoretical Chemistry, held until 1973 by Lars Onsager.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Onsager, who much like Gibbs, focused on applying new mathematical ideas to problems in physical chemistry, won the 1968 Nobel Prize in chemistry.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In addition to establishing the Josiah Willard Gibbs Laboratories and the J.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Willard Gibbs Assistant Professorship in Mathematics, Yale has also hosted two symposia dedicated to Gibbs's life and work, one in 1989 and another on the centenary of his death, in 2003.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Willard Gibbs Professorship of Thermomechanics, held as of 2014 by Bernard Coleman.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs was elected in 1950 to the Hall of Fame for Great Americans.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The oceanographic research ship USNS *Josiah Willard Gibbs* (T-AGOR-1) was in service with the United States Navy from 1958 to 1971.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs crater, near the eastern limb of the Moon, was named in the scientist's honor in 1964.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Edward Guggenheim introduced the symbol *G* for the Gibbs free energy in 1933, and this was used also by Dirk ter Haar in 1966.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] This notation is now universal and is recommended by the IUPAC.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1960, William Giauque and others suggested the name "gibbs" (abbreviated gbs.) for the unit of entropy calorie per kelvin, but this usage did not become common, and the corresponding SI unit joule per kelvin carries no special name.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1954, a year before his death, Albert Einstein was asked by an interviewer who were the greatest thinkers that he had known.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1958, USS *San Carlos* was renamed USNS *Josiah Willard Gibbs* and re-designated as an oceanographic research ship.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1909, the American historian and novelist Henry Adams finished an essay entitled "The Rule of Phase Applied to History", in which he sought to apply Gibbs's phase rule and other thermodynamic concepts to a general theory of human history.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] William James, Henry Bumstead, and others criticized both Adams's tenuous grasp of the scientific concepts that he invoked, as well as the arbitrariness of his application of those concepts as metaphors for the evolution of human thought and society.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The essay remained unpublished until it appeared posthumously in 1919, in *The Degradation of the Democratic Dogma*, edited by Henry Adams's younger brother Brooks.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In the 1930s, feminist poet Muriel Rukeyser became fascinated by Willard Gibbs and wrote a long poem about his life and work ("Gibbs", included in the collection *A Turning Wind*, published in 1939), as well as a book-length biography (*Willard Gibbs*, 1942).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 1946, *Fortune* magazine illustrated a cover story on "Fundamental Science" with a representation of the thermodynamic surface that Maxwell had built based on Gibbs's proposal.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs's nephew, Ralph Gibbs Van Name, a professor of physical chemistry at Yale, was unhappy with Rukeyser's biography, in part because of her lack of scientific training.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Van Name had withheld the family papers from her and, after her book was published in 1942 to positive literary but mixed scientific reviews, he tried to encourage Gibbs's former students to produce a more technically oriented biography.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Rukeyser's approach to Gibbs was also sharply criticized by Gibbs's former student and protégé Edwin Wilson.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] With Van Name's and Wilson's encouragement, physicist Lynde Wheeler published a new biography of Gibbs in 1951.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Both Gibbs and Rukeyser's biography of him figure prominently in the poetry collection *True North* (1997) by Stephanie Strickland.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In fiction, Gibbs appears as the mentor to character Kit Traverse in Thomas Pynchon's novel *Against the Day* (2006).
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] That novel also prominently discusses the birefringence of Iceland spar, an optical phenomenon that Gibbs investigated.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] In 2005, the United States Postal Service issued the *American Scientists* commemorative postage stamp series designed by artist Victor Stabin, depicting Gibbs, John von Neumann, Barbara McClintock, and Richard Feynman.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The first day of issue ceremony for the series was held on May 4 at Yale University's Luce Hall and was attended by John Marburger, scientific advisor to the president of the United States, Rick Levin, president of Yale, and family members of the scientists honored, including physician John W.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Gibbs, a distant cousin of Willard Gibbs.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Jolls, a professor of chemical engineering at Iowa State University and an expert on graphical methods in thermodynamics, consulted on the design of the stamp honoring Gibbs.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] The stamp identifies Gibbs as a "thermodynamicist" and features a diagram from the 4th edition of Maxwell's *Theory of Heat*, published in 1875, which illustrates Gibbs's thermodynamic surface for water.
[src:response-reactions/josiah-willard-gibbs] Microprinting on the collar of Gibbs's portrait depicts his original mathematical equation for the change in the energy of a substance in terms of its entropy and the other state variables.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In chemistry, **Le Chatelier's principle** (pronounced UK: /lə ʃæˈtɛljeɪ/ or US: /ˈʃɑːtəljeɪ/) is a principle used to predict the effect of a change in conditions on chemical equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Other names include **Chatelier's principle**, **Braun–Le Chatelier principle, Le Chatelier–Braun principle** or the **equilibrium law**.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In scenarios outside thermodynamic equilibrium, there can arise phenomena in contradiction to an over-general statement of Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Le Chatelier's principle is sometimes alluded to in discussions of topics other than thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The response illustrates 'moderation' in ways evident in two related thermodynamic equilibria.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] To give this scenario physical meaning, the 'driving' variable and the 'moderating' variable must be subject to separate independent experimental controls and measurements.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The principle can be stated in two ways which are formally different but substantially equivalent, and, in a sense, mutually 'reciprocal'.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The two ways illustrate the Maxwell relations, and the stability of thermodynamic equilibrium according to the second law of thermodynamics, evident as the spread of energy amongst the state variables of the system in response to an imposed change.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The two ways of statement differ in their experimental protocols.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] They share an *index protocol* (denoted ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }),$ which may be described as 'changed driver, moderation permitted'.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The two ways of statement differ in their respective *compared protocols*.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] This way compares ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }$ with ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {n} },$ to compare the effects of the imposed the change $\Delta L$ with and without moderation.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] This way also uses two experimental protocols, ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }$ and ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {f} }$ , to compare the index effect $\delta _{\mathrm {i} }M$ with the effect $\delta _{\mathrm {f} }M$ of 'moderation' alone.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The *index protocol* ${\mathcal {P}}_{\mathrm {i} }$ is executed first; the response of prime interest, $\delta _{\mathrm {i} }M,$ is observed, and the response $\Delta X$ of the 'moderating' variable is also measured.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The duration of adjustment depends on the strength of the negative feedback to the initial shock.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] While well rooted in chemical equilibrium, Le Chatelier's principle can also be used in describing mechanical systems, in that a system put under stress will respond in such a way as to reduce or minimize that stress.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Moreover, the response will generally be enacted through the mechanism that most easily relieves that stress.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Shear pins and other such sacrificial devices are design elements that protect systems against stress applied in undesired manners to relieve it so as to prevent more extensive damage to the entire system, a practical engineering application of Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Changing the concentration of a chemical will shift the equilibrium to the side (reactants or products) that would counter that change in concentration.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The chemical system will attempt to partly oppose the change that affected the original state of equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In turn, the rate of reaction, extent, and yield of products will be altered corresponding to the impact on the system.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Suppose we were to increase the concentration of CO in the system.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Using Le Chatelier's principle, we can predict that the concentration of methanol will increase, decreasing the total change in CO.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] If we are to add a chemical species to the overall reaction, the reaction will favor the side opposing the addition of the species.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Likewise, the subtraction of a species would cause the reaction to "fill the gap" and favor the side where the species was reduced.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] This observation is supported by the collision theory.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] As the concentration of CO is increased, the frequency of successful collisions of that reactant would increase also, allowing for an increase in forward reaction, and generation of the product.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Even if the desired product is not thermodynamically favored, the end-product can be obtained if it is continuously removed from the solution.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The effect of a change in concentration is often exploited synthetically for condensation reactions (i.e., reactions that extrude water) that are equilibrium processes (such as the formation of an ester from carboxylic acid and alcohol, or the formation of an imine from an amine and aldehyde).
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] This can be achieved by physically sequestering water, by adding desiccants like anhydrous magnesium sulfate or molecular sieves, or by continuous removal of water by distillation, often facilitated by a Dean-Stark apparatus.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The effect of changing the temperature in the equilibrium can be made clear by 1) incorporating heat as either a reactant or a product, and 2) assuming that an increase in temperature increases the heat content of a system.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] When the reaction is exothermic (Δ*H* is negative and energy is released), heat is included as a product, and when the reaction is endothermic (Δ*H* is positive and energy is consumed), heat is included as a reactant.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Hence, whether increasing or decreasing the temperature would favor the forward or the reverse reaction can be determined by applying the same principle as with concentration changes.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] If the temperature were increased, the heat content of the system would increase, so the system would consume some of that heat by shifting the equilibrium to the left, thereby producing less ammonia.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In exothermic reactions, an increase in temperature decreases the equilibrium constant *K*, whereas in endothermic reactions, an increase in temperature increases *K*.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Le Chatelier's principle applied to changes in concentration or pressure can be understood by giving *K* a constant value.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The effect of temperature on equilibria, however, involves a change in the equilibrium constant.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The dependence of *K* on temperature is determined by the sign of Δ*H*.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The theoretical basis of this dependence is given by the Van 't Hoff equation.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The equilibrium concentrations of the products and reactants do not directly depend on the total pressure of the system.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] They may depend on the partial pressure of the products and reactants, but if the number of moles of gaseous reactants is equal to the number of moles of gaseous products, pressure has no effect on equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Changing total pressure by adding an inert gas at constant volume does not affect the equilibrium concentrations (see § Effect of adding an inert gas).
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Changing total pressure by changing the volume of the system changes the partial pressures of the products and reactants and can affect the equilibrium concentrations (see § Effect of change in volume below).
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Changing the volume of the system changes the partial pressures of the products and reactants and can affect the equilibrium concentrations.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] With a pressure increase due to a decrease in volume, the side of the equilibrium with fewer moles is more favorable, whereas with a pressure decrease due to an increase in volume, the side with more moles is more favorable.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] There is no effect on a reaction where the number of moles of gas is the same on each side of the chemical equation.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Note the number of moles of gas on the left-hand side and the number of moles of gas on the right-hand side.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] When the volume of the system is changed, the partial pressures of the gases change.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] If we were to decrease pressure by increasing volume, the equilibrium of the above reaction would shift to the left, because the reactant side has a greater number of moles than the product side does.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The system tries to counteract the decrease in partial pressure of gas molecules by shifting to the side that exerts greater pressure.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Similarly, if we were to increase pressure by decreasing volume, the equilibrium shifts to the right, counteracting the pressure increase by shifting to the side with fewer moles of gas that exert less pressure.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] If the volume is increased because there are more moles of gas on the reactant side, this change is more significant in the denominator of the equilibrium constant expression, causing a shift in equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] An inert gas (or noble gas), such as helium, is one that does not react with other elements or compounds.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Adding an inert gas into a gas-phase equilibrium at constant volume does not result in a shift.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] This is because the addition of a non-reactive gas does not change the equilibrium equation, as the inert gas appears on both sides of the chemical reaction equation.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] For example, if A and B react to form C and D, but X does not participate in the reaction: ${\ce {{\mathit {a}}A{}+{\mathit {b}}B{}+{\mathit {x}}X<=>{\mathit {c}}C{}+{\mathit {d}}D{}+{\mathit {x}}X}}$ .
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] While it is true that the total pressure of the system increases, the total pressure does not have any effect on the equilibrium constant; rather, it is a change in partial pressures that will cause a shift in the equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] If, however, the volume is allowed to increase in the process, the partial pressures of all gases would be decreased resulting in a shift towards the side with the greater number of moles of gas.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The shift will never occur on the side with fewer moles of gas.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] It is also known as Le Chatelier's postulate.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] A catalyst increases the rate of a reaction without being consumed in the reaction.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The use of a catalyst does not affect the position and composition of the equilibrium of a reaction, because both the forward and backward reactions are sped up by the same factor.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In the above reaction, iron (Fe) and molybdenum (Mo) will function as catalysts if present.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] They will accelerate any reactions, but they do not affect the state of the equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Le Chatelier's principle refers to states of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The latter are stable against perturbations that satisfy certain criteria; this is essential to the definition of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] It states that changes in the temperature, pressure, volume, or concentration of a system will result in predictable and opposing changes in the system in order to achieve a new equilibrium state.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] A simple body or a complex thermodynamic system can also be in a stationary state with non-zero rates of flow and chemical reaction; sometimes the word "equilibrium" is used in reference to such a state, though by definition it is not a thermodynamic equilibrium state.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Sometimes, it is proposed to consider Le Chatelier's principle for such states.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] For this exercise, rates of flow and of chemical reaction must be considered.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Such rates are not supplied by equilibrium thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] For such states, there are no simple statements that echo Le Chatelier's principle.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Prigogine and Defay demonstrate that such a scenario may exhibit moderation, or may exhibit a measured amount of anti-moderation, though not a run-away anti-moderation that goes to completion.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The example analysed by Prigogine and Defay is the Haber process.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] This situation is clarified by considering two basic methods of analysis of a process.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] One is the classical approach of Gibbs, the other uses the near- or local equilibrium approach of De Donder.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The Gibbs approach requires thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The Gibbs approach is reliable within its proper scope, thermodynamic equilibrium, though of course it does not cover non-equilibrium scenarios.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The De Donder approach can cover equilibrium scenarios, but also covers non-equilibrium scenarios in which there is only local thermodynamic equilibrium, and not thermodynamic equilibrium proper.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The De Donder approach allows state variables called extents of reaction to be independent variables, though in the Gibbs approach, such variables are not independent.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Thermodynamic non-equilibrium scenarios can contradict an over-general statement of Le Chatelier's Principle.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] The concept of systemic maintenance of a stable steady state despite perturbations has a variety of names, and has been studied in a variety of contexts, chiefly in the natural sciences.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In chemistry, the principle is used to manipulate the outcomes of reversible reactions, often to increase their yield.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In pharmacology, the binding of ligands to receptors may shift the equilibrium according to Le Chatelier's principle, thereby explaining the diverse phenomena of receptor activation and desensitization.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In biology, the concept of homeostasis is different from Le Chatelier's principle, in that homoeostasis is generally maintained by processes of active character, as distinct from the passive or dissipative character of the processes described by Le Chatelier's principle in thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In economics, even further from thermodynamics, allusion to the principle is sometimes regarded as helping explain the price equilibrium of efficient economic systems.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In some dynamic systems, the end-state cannot be determined from the shock or perturbation.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] In economics, a similar concept also named after Le Chatelier was introduced by American economist Paul Samuelson in 1947.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] There the generalized Le Chatelier principle is for a maximum condition of economic equilibrium: Where all unknowns of a function are independently variable, auxiliary constraints—"just-binding" in leaving initial equilibrium unchanged—reduce the response to a parameter change.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Thus, factor-demand and commodity-supply elasticities are hypothesized to be lower in the short run than in the long run because of the fixed-cost constraint in the short run.
[src:response-reactions/le-chatelier-principle] Since the change of the value of an objective function in a neighbourhood of the maximum position is described by the envelope theorem, Le Chatelier's principle can be shown to be a corollary thereof.
[src:response-reactions/response-reactions] It is based on detailed analysis of the Hessian determinant, using either the Gibbs or the De Donder method of analysis.
[src:response-reactions/response-reactions] The theory derives the sensitivity coefficient as the sum of the contributions of individual RERs.
[src:response-reactions/response-reactions] Thus phenomena which are in contradiction to over-general statements of the Le Chatelier principle can be interpreted.
[src:response-reactions/response-reactions] With the help of RERs the equilibrium coupling was defined.
[src:response-reactions/response-reactions] RERs could be derived based either on the species, or on the stoichiometrically independent reactions of a parallel system.
[src:response-reactions/response-reactions] The set of RERs is unambiguous in a given system; and the number of them (M) is $S \choose C+1$ , where S denotes the number of species and C refers to the number of components.
[src:response-reactions/response-reactions] In the case of three-component systems, RERs can be visualized on a triangle diagram.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In thermodynamic equilibrium, there are no net macroscopic flows of mass nor of energy within a system or between systems.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Systems can be in one kind of mutual equilibrium, while not in others.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In thermodynamic equilibrium, all kinds of equilibrium hold at once and indefinitely, unless disturbed by a thermodynamic operation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In a macroscopic equilibrium, perfectly or almost perfectly balanced microscopic exchanges occur; this is the physical explanation of the notion of macroscopic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A thermodynamic system in a state of internal thermodynamic equilibrium has a spatially uniform temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Its intensive properties, other than temperature, may be driven to spatial inhomogeneity by an unchanging long-range force field imposed on it by its surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In systems that are at a state of non-equilibrium there are, by contrast, net flows of matter or energy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If such changes can be triggered to occur in a system in which they are not already occurring, the system is said to be in a "meta-stable equilibrium".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Though not a widely named "law," it is an axiom of thermodynamics that there exist states of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The second law of thermodynamics states that, in an isolated system, when partitions are removed between equilibrated subsystems in different states, the system spontaneously equilibrates (achieves thermodynamic equilibrium), accompanied by an increase in the system's entropy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Classical thermodynamics deals with states of dynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The state of a system at thermodynamic equilibrium is the one for which some thermodynamic potential is minimized (in the absence of an applied voltage), or for which the entropy (*S*) is maximized, for specified conditions.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] where *T* denotes the absolute thermodynamic temperature, *P* the pressure, *S* the entropy, *V* the volume, and *U* the internal energy of the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In other words, $\Delta G=0$ is a necessary condition for chemical equilibrium under these conditions (in the absence of an applied voltage).
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Thermodynamic equilibrium is the unique stable stationary state that is approached or eventually reached as the system interacts with its surroundings over a long time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The above-mentioned potentials are mathematically constructed to be the thermodynamic quantities that are minimized under the particular conditions in the specified surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Often the surroundings of a thermodynamic system may also be regarded as another thermodynamic system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In this view, one may consider the system and its surroundings as two systems in mutual contact, with long-range forces also linking them.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The enclosure of the system is the surface of contiguity or boundary between the two systems.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In the thermodynamic formalism, that surface is regarded as having specific properties of permeability.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, the surface of contiguity may be supposed to be permeable only to heat, allowing energy to transfer only as heat.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Then the two systems are said to be in thermal equilibrium when the long-range forces are unchanging in time and the transfer of energy as heat between them has slowed and eventually stopped permanently; this is an example of a contact equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Other kinds of contact equilibrium are defined by other kinds of specific permeability.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] When two systems are in contact equilibrium with respect to a particular kind of permeability, they have common values of the intensive variable that belongs to that particular kind of permeability.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Examples of such intensive variables are temperature, pressure, chemical potential.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A contact equilibrium may be regarded also as an exchange equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] There is a zero balance of rate of transfer of some quantity between the two systems in contact equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, for a wall permeable only to heat, the rates of diffusion of internal energy as heat between the two systems are equal and opposite.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] An adiabatic wall between the two systems is 'permeable' only to energy transferred as work; at mechanical equilibrium the rates of transfer of energy as work between them are equal and opposite.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the wall is a simple wall, then the rates of transfer of volume across it are also equal and opposite; and the pressures on either side of it are equal.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the adiabatic wall is more complicated, with a sort of leverage, having an area-ratio, then the pressures of the two systems in exchange equilibrium are in the inverse ratio of the volume exchange ratio; this keeps the zero balance of rates of transfer as work.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A radiative exchange can occur between two otherwise separate systems.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Radiative exchange equilibrium prevails when the two systems have the same temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A collection of matter may be entirely isolated from its surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If it has been left undisturbed for an indefinitely long time, classical thermodynamics postulates that it is in a state in which no changes occur within it, and there are no flows within it.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This is a thermodynamic state of internal equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] (This postulate is sometimes, but not often, called the "minus first" law of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Such states are a principal concern in what is known as classical or equilibrium thermodynamics, for they are the only states of the system that are regarded as well defined in that subject.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A system in contact equilibrium with another system can by a thermodynamic operation be isolated, and upon the event of isolation, no change occurs in it.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A system in a relation of contact equilibrium with another system may thus also be regarded as being in its own state of internal thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The thermodynamic formalism allows that a system may have contact with several other systems at once, which may or may not also have mutual contact, the contacts having respectively different permeabilities.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If these systems are all jointly isolated from the rest of the world those of them that are in contact then reach respective contact equilibria with one another.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If several systems are free of adiabatic walls between each other, but are jointly isolated from the rest of the world, then they reach a state of multiple contact equilibrium, and they have a common temperature, a total internal energy, and a total entropy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Amongst intensive variables, this is a unique property of temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It holds even in the presence of long-range forces.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] (That is, there is no "force" that can maintain temperature discrepancies.) For example, in a system in thermodynamic equilibrium in a vertical gravitational field, the pressure on the top wall is less than that on the bottom wall, but the temperature is the same everywhere.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A thermodynamic operation may occur as an event restricted to the walls that are within the surroundings, directly affecting neither the walls of contact of the system of interest with its surroundings, nor its interior, and occurring within a definitely limited time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, an immovable adiabatic wall may be placed or removed within the surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Consequent upon such an operation restricted to the surroundings, the system may be for a time driven away from its own initial internal state of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Then, according to the second law of thermodynamics, the whole undergoes changes and eventually reaches a new and final equilibrium with the surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Following Planck, this consequent train of events is called a natural thermodynamic process.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A natural process proceeds at a finite rate for the main part of its course.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It is thereby radically different from a fictive quasi-static 'process' that proceeds infinitely slowly throughout its course, and is fictively 'reversible'.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Classical thermodynamics allows that even though a process may take a very long time to settle to thermodynamic equilibrium, if the main part of its course is at a finite rate, then it is considered to be natural, and to be subject to the second law of thermodynamics, and thereby irreversible.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Engineered machines and artificial devices and manipulations are permitted within the surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The allowance of such operations and devices in the surroundings but not in the system is the reason why Kelvin in one of his statements of the second law of thermodynamics spoke of "inanimate" agency; a system in thermodynamic equilibrium is inanimate.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Otherwise, a thermodynamic operation may directly affect a wall of the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It is often convenient to suppose that some of the surrounding subsystems are so much larger than the system that the process can affect the intensive variables only of the surrounding subsystems, and they are then called reservoirs for relevant intensive variables.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It can be useful to distinguish between global and local thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In thermodynamics, exchanges within a system and between the system and the outside are controlled by intensive parameters.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] As an example, temperature controls heat exchanges.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the description of the system requires variations in the intensive parameters that are too large, the very assumptions upon which the definitions of these intensive parameters are based will break down, and the system will be in neither global nor local equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, it takes a certain number of collisions for a particle to equilibrate to its surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the average distance it has moved during these collisions removes it from the neighborhood it is equilibrating to, it will never equilibrate, and there will be no LTE.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Temperature is, by definition, proportional to the average internal energy of an equilibrated neighborhood.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Since there is no equilibrated neighborhood, the concept of temperature doesn't hold, and the temperature becomes undefined.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This local equilibrium may apply only to a certain subset of particles in the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, LTE is usually applied only to massive particles.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In a radiating gas, the photons being emitted and absorbed by the gas do not need to be in a thermodynamic equilibrium with each other or with the massive particles of the gas for LTE to exist.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In some cases, it is not considered necessary for free electrons to be in equilibrium with the much more massive atoms or molecules for LTE to exist.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] As an example, LTE will exist in a glass of water that contains a melting ice cube.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The temperature inside the glass can be defined at any point, but it is colder near the ice cube than far away from it.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If energies of the molecules located near a given point are observed, they will be distributed according to the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution for a certain temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the energies of the molecules located near another point are observed, they will be distributed according to the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution for another temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Local thermodynamic equilibrium does not require either local or global stationarity.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In other words, each small locality need not have a constant temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] However, it does require that each small locality change slowly enough to practically sustain its local Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution of molecular velocities.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A global non-equilibrium state can be stably stationary only if it is maintained by exchanges between the system and the outside.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, a globally-stable stationary state could be maintained inside the glass of water by continuously adding finely powdered ice into it to compensate for the melting, and continuously draining off the meltwater.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Natural transport phenomena may lead a system from local to global thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Going back to our example, the diffusion of heat will lead our glass of water toward global thermodynamic equilibrium, a state in which the temperature of the glass is completely homogeneous.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Some accounts of thermodynamic equilibrium often enough make provisos or reservations to their statements.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Some writers leave such reservations merely implied or more or less unstated.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Callen writes in this context: "In actuality, few systems are in absolute and true equilibrium." He refers to radioactive processes and remarks that they may take "cosmic times to complete, [and] generally can be ignored".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He adds "In practice, the criterion for equilibrium is circular.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Pippard writes in *The Elements of Classical Thermodynamics*: "Given long enough a supercooled vapour will eventually condense, ... .
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The time involved may be so enormous, however, perhaps 10100 years or more, ... .
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He observes that thermonuclear processes often occur so slowly that they can be ignored in thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Tisza: "... in the discussion of phenomena near absolute zero.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The most general kind of thermodynamic equilibrium of a system is through contact with the surroundings that allows simultaneous passages of all chemical substances and all kinds of energy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A system in thermodynamic equilibrium may move with uniform acceleration through space but must not change its shape or size while doing so; thus it is defined by a rigid volume in space.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It may lie within external fields of force, determined by external factors of far greater extent than the system itself, so that events within the system cannot in an appreciable amount affect the external fields of force.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The system can be in thermodynamic equilibrium only if the external force fields are uniform, and are determining its uniform acceleration, or if it lies in a non-uniform force field but is held stationary there by local forces, such as mechanical pressures, on its surface.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Thermodynamic equilibrium is a primitive notion of the theory of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Morse: "It should be emphasized that the fact that there are thermodynamic states, ..., and the fact that there are thermodynamic variables which are uniquely specified by the equilibrium state ... are *not* conclusions deduced logically from some philosophical first principles.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] They are conclusions ineluctably drawn from more than two centuries of experiments." This means that thermodynamic equilibrium is not to be defined solely in terms of other theoretical concepts of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Bailyn proposes a fundamental law of thermodynamics that defines and postulates the existence of states of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Textbook definitions of thermodynamic equilibrium are often stated carefully, with some reservation or other.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Münster writes: "An isolated system is in thermodynamic equilibrium when, in the system, no changes of state are occurring at a measurable rate." There are two reservations stated here; the system is isolated; any changes of state are immeasurably slow.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He discusses the second proviso by giving an account of a mixture oxygen and hydrogen at room temperature in the absence of a catalyst.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Münster points out that a thermodynamic equilibrium state is described by fewer macroscopic variables than is any other state of a given system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This is partly, but not entirely, because all flows within and through the system are zero.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Haase's presentation of thermodynamics does not start with a restriction to thermodynamic equilibrium because he intends to allow for non-equilibrium thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He considers an arbitrary system with time invariant properties.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He tests it for thermodynamic equilibrium by cutting it off from all external influences, except external force fields.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If after insulation, nothing changes, he says that the system was in *equilibrium*.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In a section headed "Thermodynamic equilibrium", H.B.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Callen defines equilibrium states in a paragraph.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He points out that they "are determined by intrinsic factors" within the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] They are "terminal states", towards which the systems evolve, over time, which may occur with "glacial slowness".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This statement does not explicitly say that for thermodynamic equilibrium, the system must be isolated; Callen does not spell out what he means by the words "intrinsic factors".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Adkins, explicitly allows thermodynamic equilibrium to occur in a system which is not isolated.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] His system is, however, closed with respect to transfer of matter.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He writes: "In general, the approach to thermodynamic equilibrium will involve both thermal and work-like interactions with the surroundings." He distinguishes such thermodynamic equilibrium from thermal equilibrium, in which only thermal contact is mediating transfer of energy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Like Münster, Partington also refers to the mixture of oxygen and hydrogen.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Crawford has a section headed "Thermodynamic Equilibrium".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A monograph on classical thermodynamics by H.A.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Buchdahl considers the "equilibrium of a thermodynamic system", without actually writing the phrase "thermodynamic equilibrium".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Referring to systems closed to exchange of matter, Buchdahl writes: "If a system is in a terminal condition which is properly static, it will be said to be in *equilibrium*." Buchdahl's monograph also discusses amorphous glass, for the purposes of thermodynamic description.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Münster carefully extends his definition of thermodynamic equilibrium for isolated systems by introducing a concept of *contact equilibrium*.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This specifies particular processes that are allowed when considering thermodynamic equilibrium for non-isolated systems, with special concern for open systems, which may gain or lose matter from or to their surroundings.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A contact equilibrium is between the system of interest and a system in the surroundings, brought into contact with the system of interest, the contact being through a special kind of wall; for the rest, the whole joint system is isolated.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Walls of this special kind were also considered by C.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Carathéodory, and are mentioned by other writers also.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] They may be permeable only to mechanical work, or only to heat, or only to some particular chemical substance.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Each contact equilibrium defines an intensive parameter; for example, a wall permeable only to heat defines an empirical temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A contact equilibrium can exist for each chemical constituent of the system of interest.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In a contact equilibrium, despite the possible exchange through the selectively permeable wall, the system of interest is changeless, as if it were in isolated thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This definition does not consider the most general kind of thermodynamic equilibrium, which is through unselective contacts.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This definition does not simply state that no current of matter or energy exists in the interior or at the boundaries; but it is compatible with the following definition, which does so state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Zemansky also distinguishes mechanical, chemical, and thermal equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He then writes: "When the conditions for all three types of equilibrium are satisfied, the system is said to be in a state of thermodynamic equilibrium".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Morse writes that thermodynamics is concerned with "*states of thermodynamic equilibrium*".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He also uses the phrase "thermal equilibrium" while discussing transfer of energy as heat between a body and a heat reservoir in its surroundings, though not explicitly defining a special term 'thermal equilibrium'.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Waldram writes of "a definite thermodynamic state".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He defines the term "thermal equilibrium" for a system "when its observables have ceased to change over time".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] But shortly below that definition he writes of a piece of glass that has not yet reached its "*full* thermodynamic equilibrium state".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Bailyn writes: "Each intensive variable has its own type of equilibrium." He then defines thermal equilibrium, mechanical equilibrium, and material equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Accordingly, he writes: "If all the intensive variables become uniform, *thermodynamic equilibrium* is said to exist." He is not here considering the presence of an external force field.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] They do not discuss the possibility of changes that occur with "glacial slowness", and proceed beyond the time period allotted for experimentation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] They note that for two systems in contact, there exists a small subclass of intensive properties such that if all those of that small subclass are respectively equal, then all respective intensive properties are equal.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] States of thermodynamic equilibrium may be defined by this subclass, provided some other conditions are satisfied.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A thermodynamic system consisting of a single phase in the absence of external forces, in its own internal thermodynamic equilibrium, is homogeneous.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This means that the material in any small volume element of the system can be interchanged with the material of any other geometrically congruent volume element of the system, and the effect is to leave the system thermodynamically unchanged.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In general, a strong external force field makes a system of a single phase in its own internal thermodynamic equilibrium inhomogeneous with respect to some intensive variables.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, a relatively dense component of a mixture can be concentrated by centrifugation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Such equilibrium inhomogeneity, induced by external forces, does not occur for the intensive variable temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Though referring to temperature, Planck did not there explicitly refer to the concept of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Although thermodynamic laws are immutable, systems can be created that delay the time to reach thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Howald conceived of a system called "The Fizz Keeper" consisting of a cap with a nozzle that can re-pressurize any standard bottle of carbonated beverage.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Nitrogen and oxygen, which air are mostly made out of, would keep getting pumped in, which would slow down the rate at which the carbon dioxide fizzles out of the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This is possible because the thermodynamic equilibrium between the unconverted and converted carbon dioxide inside the bottle would stay the same.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] To come to this conclusion, he also appeals to Henry's Law, which states that gases dissolve in direct proportion to their partial pressures.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] By influencing the partial pressure on the top of a closed system, this would help slow down the rate of fizzing out of carbonated beverages which is governed by thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The equilibria of carbon dioxide and other gases would not change, however the partial pressure on top would slow down the rate of dissolution extending the time a gas stays in a particular state due to the nature of thermal equilibrium of the remainder of the beverage.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The equilibrium constant of carbon dioxide would be completely independent of the nitrogen and oxygen pumped into the system, which would slow down the diffusion of gas, and yet not have an impact on the thermodynamics of the entire system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The temperature within a system in thermodynamic equilibrium is uniform in space as well as in time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In a system in its own state of internal thermodynamic equilibrium, there are no net internal macroscopic flows.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In particular, this means that all local parts of the system are in mutual radiative exchange equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This means that the temperature of the system is spatially uniform.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This is so in all cases, including those of non-uniform external force fields.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For an externally imposed gravitational field, this may be proved in macroscopic thermodynamic terms, by the calculus of variations, using the method of Langrangian multipliers.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Considerations of kinetic theory or statistical mechanics also support this statement.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In his exposition of his scheme of closed system equilibrium thermodynamics, C.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Carathéodory initially postulates that experiment reveals that a definite number of real variables define the states that are the points of the manifold of equilibria.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In the words of Prigogine and Defay (1945): "It is a matter of experience that when we have specified a certain number of macroscopic properties of a system, then all the other properties are fixed." As noted above, according to A.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Münster, the number of variables needed to define a thermodynamic equilibrium is the least for any state of a given isolated system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Oppenheim point out that a state of thermodynamic equilibrium may be defined by a special subclass of intensive variables, with a definite number of members in that subclass.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the thermodynamic equilibrium lies in an external force field, it is only the temperature that can in general be expected to be spatially uniform.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Intensive variables other than temperature will in general be non-uniform if the external force field is non-zero.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In such a case, in general, additional variables are needed to describe the spatial non-uniformity.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Partington points out that a state of thermodynamic equilibrium is stable against small transient perturbations.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Without this condition, in general, experiments intended to study systems in thermodynamic equilibrium are in severe difficulties.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] When a body of material starts from a non-equilibrium state of inhomogeneity or chemical non-equilibrium, and is then isolated, it spontaneously evolves towards its own internal state of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It is not necessary that all aspects of internal thermodynamic equilibrium be reached simultaneously; some can be established before others.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, in many cases of such evolution, internal mechanical equilibrium is established much more rapidly than the other aspects of the eventual thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Another example is that, in many cases of such evolution, thermal equilibrium is reached much more rapidly than chemical equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In an isolated system, thermodynamic equilibrium by definition persists over an indefinitely long time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In classical physics it is often convenient to ignore the effects of measurement and this is assumed in the present account.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] To consider the notion of fluctuations in an isolated thermodynamic system, a convenient example is a system specified by its extensive state variables, internal energy, volume, and mass composition.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] By definition, they combine with time-invariant nominal values of their conjugate intensive functions of state, inverse temperature, pressure divided by temperature, and the chemical potentials divided by temperature, so as to exactly obey the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] But the laws of thermodynamics, combined with the values of the specifying extensive variables of state, are not sufficient to provide knowledge of those nominal values.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Further information is needed, namely, of the constitutive properties of the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It may be admitted that on repeated measurement of those conjugate intensive functions of state, they are found to have slightly different values from time to time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Such variability is regarded as due to internal fluctuations.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The different measured values average to their nominal values.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the system is truly macroscopic as postulated by classical thermodynamics, then the fluctuations are too small to detect macroscopically.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In effect, the molecular nature of matter and the quantal nature of momentum transfer have vanished from sight, too small to see.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the system is repeatedly subdivided, eventually a system is produced that is small enough to exhibit obvious fluctuations.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This is a mesoscopic level of investigation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The fluctuations are then directly dependent on the natures of the various walls of the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The precise choice of independent state variables is then important.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] At this stage, statistical features of the laws of thermodynamics become apparent.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] If the mesoscopic system is further repeatedly divided, eventually a microscopic system is produced.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Then the molecular character of matter and the quantal nature of momentum transfer become important in the processes of fluctuation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] One has left the realm of classical or macroscopic thermodynamics, and one needs quantum statistical mechanics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The fluctuations can become relatively dominant, and questions of measurement become important.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The statement that 'the system is its own internal thermodynamic equilibrium' may be taken to mean that 'indefinitely many such measurements have been taken from time to time, with no trend in time in the various measured values'.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This is because the single measurements might have been made during a slight fluctuation, away from another set of nominal values of those conjugate intensive functions of state, that is due to unknown and different constitutive properties.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A single measurement cannot tell whether that might be so, unless there is also knowledge of the nominal values that belong to the equilibrium state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Thermal equilibrium is achieved when two systems in thermal contact with each other cease to have a net exchange of energy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It follows that if two systems are in thermal equilibrium, then their temperatures are the same.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Thermal equilibrium occurs when a system's macroscopic thermal observables have ceased to change with time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For example, an ideal gas whose distribution function has stabilised to a specific Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution would be in thermal equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] This outcome allows a single temperature and pressure to be attributed to the whole system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] For an isolated body, it is quite possible for mechanical equilibrium to be reached before thermal equilibrium is reached, but eventually, all aspects of equilibrium, including thermal equilibrium, are necessary for thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] An explicit distinction between 'thermal equilibrium' and 'thermodynamic equilibrium' is made by B.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He considers two systems in thermal contact, one a thermometer, the other a system in which there are several occurring irreversible processes, entailing non-zero fluxes; the two systems are separated by a wall permeable only to heat.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] He considers the case in which, over the time scale of interest, it happens that both the thermometer reading and the irreversible processes are steady.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Then there is thermal equilibrium without thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] In other words, thermodynamics has no meaning for such a process." This illustrates the importance for thermodynamics of the concept of temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] A system's internal state of thermodynamic equilibrium should be distinguished from a "stationary state" in which thermodynamic parameters are unchanging in time but the system is not isolated, so that there are, into and out of the system, non-zero macroscopic fluxes which are constant in time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Non-equilibrium thermodynamics is a branch of thermodynamics that deals with systems that are not in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Most systems found in nature are not in thermodynamic equilibrium because they are changing or can be triggered to change over time, and are continuously and discontinuously subject to flux of matter and energy to and from other systems.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] The thermodynamic study of non-equilibrium systems requires more general concepts than are dealt with by equilibrium thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Many natural systems still today remain beyond the scope of currently known macroscopic thermodynamic methods.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] Laws governing systems which are far from equilibrium are also debatable.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] One of the guiding principles for these systems is the maximum entropy production principle.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamic-equilibrium] It states that a non-equilibrium system evolves such as to maximize its entropy production.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Historically, thermodynamics developed out of a desire to increase the efficiency of early steam engines, particularly through the work of French physicist Sadi Carnot (1824).
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] His most important paper, "On the Moving Force of Heat", published in 1850, first stated the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In 1865 he named the concept of entropy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In 1870 he introduced the virial theorem, which applied to heat.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The initial application of thermodynamics to mechanical heat engines was quickly extended to the study of chemical compounds and chemical reactions.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Chemical thermodynamics studies the nature of the role of entropy in the process of chemical reactions and has provided the bulk of expansion and knowledge of the field.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Other formulations of thermodynamics emerged.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Statistical thermodynamics, or statistical mechanics, concerns itself with statistical predictions of the collective motion of particles from their microscopic behavior.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In 1909, Constantin Carathéodory presented a purely mathematical approach in an axiomatic formulation, a description often referred to as *geometrical thermodynamics*.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A description of any thermodynamic system employs the four laws of thermodynamics that form an axiomatic basis.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The first law specifies that energy can be transferred between physical systems as heat, as work, and with the transfer of matter.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The second law defines the existence of a quantity called entropy, which describes the direction, thermodynamically, that a system can evolve and quantifies the state of order of a system and which can be used to quantify the useful work that can be extracted from the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In thermodynamics, interactions between large ensembles of objects are studied and categorized.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Central to this are the concepts of the thermodynamic *system* and its *surroundings*.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A system is composed of particles, whose average motions define its properties, and those properties are in turn related to one another through equations of state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Properties can be combined to express internal energy and thermodynamic potentials, which are useful for determining conditions for equilibrium and spontaneous processes.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] With these tools, thermodynamics can be used to describe how systems respond to changes in their environment.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] This can be applied to a wide variety of topics in science and engineering, such as engines, phase transitions, chemical reactions, transport phenomena, and even black holes.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The results of thermodynamics are essential for other fields of physics and for chemistry, chemical engineering, corrosion engineering, aerospace engineering, mechanical engineering, cell biology, biomedical engineering, materials science, and economics, to name a few.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] This article is focused mainly on classical thermodynamics which primarily studies systems in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Non-equilibrium thermodynamics is often treated as an extension of the classical treatment, but statistical mechanics has brought many advances to that field.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The history of thermodynamics as a scientific discipline generally begins with Otto von Guericke who, in 1650, built and designed the world's first vacuum pump and demonstrated a vacuum using his Magdeburg hemispheres.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Guericke was driven to make a vacuum in order to disprove Aristotle's long-held supposition that 'nature abhors a vacuum'.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Shortly after Guericke, the Anglo-Irish physicist and chemist Robert Boyle had learned of Guericke's designs and, in 1656, in coordination with English scientist Robert Hooke, built an air pump.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Using this pump, Boyle and Hooke noticed a correlation between pressure, temperature, and volume.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In time, Boyle's Law was formulated, which states that pressure and volume are inversely proportional.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Then, in 1679, based on these concepts, an associate of Boyle's named Denis Papin built a steam digester, which was a closed vessel with a tightly fitting lid that confined steam until a high pressure was generated.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Later designs implemented a steam release valve that kept the machine from exploding.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] By watching the valve rhythmically move up and down, Papin conceived of the idea of a piston and a cylinder engine.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] He did not, however, follow through with his design.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Nevertheless, in 1697, based on Papin's designs, engineer Thomas Savery built the first engine, followed by Thomas Newcomen in 1712.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Although these early engines were crude and inefficient, they attracted the attention of the leading scientists of the time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The fundamental concepts of heat capacity and latent heat, which were necessary for the development of thermodynamics, were developed by Professor Joseph Black at the University of Glasgow, where James Watt was employed as an instrument maker.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Black and Watt performed experiments together, but it was Watt who conceived the idea of the external condenser which resulted in a large increase in steam engine efficiency.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Drawing on all the previous work led Sadi Carnot, the "father of thermodynamics", to publish *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire* (1824), a discourse on heat, power, energy and engine efficiency.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The book outlined the basic energetic relations between the Carnot engine, the Carnot cycle, and motive power.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] It marked the start of thermodynamics as a modern science.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The first thermodynamic textbook was written in 1859 by William Rankine, originally trained as a physicist and a civil and mechanical engineering professor at the University of Glasgow.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The first and second laws of thermodynamics emerged simultaneously in the 1850s, primarily out of the works of William Rankine, Rudolf Clausius, and William Thomson (Lord Kelvin).
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The foundations of statistical thermodynamics were set out by physicists such as James Clerk Maxwell, Ludwig Boltzmann, Max Planck, Rudolf Clausius and J.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Clausius, who first stated the basic ideas of the second law in his paper "On the Moving Force of Heat", published in 1850, and is called "one of the founding fathers of thermodynamics", introduced the concept of entropy in 1865.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Also Pierre Duhem in the 19th century wrote about chemical thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] During the early 20th century, chemists such as Gilbert N.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Guggenheim applied the mathematical methods of Gibbs to the analysis of chemical processes.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] By a surface-level analysis, the word consists of two parts that can be traced back to Ancient Greek.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Firstly, *thermo-* ("of heat"; used in words such as *thermometer*) can be traced back to the root θέρμη *therme*, meaning "heat".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Secondly, the word *dynamics* ("science of force [or power]") can be traced back to the root δύναμις *dynamis*, meaning "power".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In 1849, the adjective *thermo-dynamic* is used by William Thomson.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In 1854, the noun *thermo-dynamics* is used by Thomson and William Rankine to represent the science of generalized heat engines.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Pierre Perrot claims that the term *thermodynamics* was coined by James Joule in 1858 to designate the science of relations between heat and power, however, Joule never used that term, but used instead the term *perfect thermo-dynamic engine* in reference to Thomson's 1849 phraseology.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The study of thermodynamic systems has developed into several related branches, each using a different fundamental model as a theoretical or experimental basis, or applying the principles to varying types of systems.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Classical thermodynamics is the description of the states of thermodynamic systems at near-equilibrium, that uses macroscopic, measurable properties.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] It is used to model exchanges of energy, work and heat based on the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The qualifier *classical* reflects the fact that it represents the first level of understanding of the subject as it developed in the 19th century and describes the changes of a system in terms of macroscopic empirical (large scale, and measurable) parameters.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A microscopic interpretation of these concepts was later provided by the development of *statistical mechanics*.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Chemical thermodynamics is the study of the interrelation of energy with chemical reactions or with a physical change of state within the confines of the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The primary objective of chemical thermodynamics is to determine the spontaneity of a given transformation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Equilibrium thermodynamics is the study of transfers of matter and energy in systems or bodies that, by agencies in their surroundings, can be driven from one state of thermodynamic equilibrium to another.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The term 'thermodynamic equilibrium' indicates a state of balance, in which all macroscopic flows are zero; in the case of the simplest systems or bodies, their intensive properties are homogeneous, and their pressures are perpendicular to their boundaries.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In an equilibrium state there are no unbalanced potentials, or driving forces, between macroscopically distinct parts of the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Most systems found in nature are not in thermodynamic equilibrium because they are not in stationary states, and are continuously and discontinuously subject to flux of matter and energy to and from other systems.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Thermodynamics is principally based on a set of four laws which are universally valid when applied to systems that fall within the constraints implied by each.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In the various theoretical descriptions of thermodynamics these laws may be expressed in seemingly differing forms, but the most prominent formulations are the following.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] This statement implies that thermal equilibrium is an equivalence relation on the set of thermodynamic systems under consideration.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Systems are said to be in equilibrium if the small, random exchanges between them (e.g.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Brownian motion) do not lead to a net change in energy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] This law is tacitly assumed in every measurement of temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Thus, if one seeks to decide whether two bodies are at the same temperature, it is not necessary to bring them into contact and measure any changes of their observable properties in time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The law provides an empirical definition of temperature, and justification for the construction of practical thermometers.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The zeroth law was not initially recognized as a separate law of thermodynamics, as its basis in thermodynamical equilibrium was implied in the other laws.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The first, second, and third laws had been explicitly stated already, and found common acceptance in the physics community before the importance of the zeroth law for the definition of temperature was realized.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] As it was impractical to renumber the other laws, it was named the *zeroth law*.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Adapted for thermodynamics, this law is an expression of the principle of conservation of energy, which states that energy can be transformed (changed from one form to another), but cannot be created or destroyed.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Internal energy is a principal property of the thermodynamic state, while heat and work are modes of energy transfer by which a process may change this state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A change of internal energy of a system may be achieved by any combination of heat added or removed and work performed on or by the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] As a function of state, the internal energy does not depend on the manner, or on the path through intermediate steps, by which the system arrived at its state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The second law refers to a system of matter and radiation, initially with inhomogeneities in temperature, pressure, chemical potential, and other intensive properties, that are due to internal 'constraints', or impermeable rigid walls, within it, or to externally imposed forces.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] For systems that are initially far from thermodynamic equilibrium, though several have been proposed, there is known no general physical principle that determines the rates of approach to thermodynamic equilibrium, and thermodynamics does not deal with such rates.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The many versions of the second law all express the general irreversibility of the transitions involved in systems approaching thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In macroscopic thermodynamics, the second law is a basic observation applicable to any actual thermodynamic process; in statistical thermodynamics, the second law is postulated to be a consequence of molecular chaos.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] This law of thermodynamics is a statistical law of nature regarding entropy and the impossibility of reaching absolute zero of temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] This law provides an absolute reference point for the determination of entropy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The entropy determined relative to this point is the absolute entropy.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Alternative definitions include "the entropy of all systems and of all states of a system is smallest at absolute zero," or equivalently "it is impossible to reach the absolute zero of temperature by any finite number of processes".
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Absolute zero, at which all activity would stop if it were possible to achieve, is −273.15 °C (degrees Celsius), or −459.67 °F (degrees Fahrenheit), or 0 K (kelvin), or 0° R (degrees Rankine).
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] An important concept in thermodynamics is the thermodynamic system, which is a precisely defined region of the universe under study.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Everything in the universe except the system is called the *surroundings*.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A system is separated from the remainder of the universe by a *boundary* which may be a physical or notional, but serve to confine the system to a finite volume.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Segments of the *boundary* are often described as *walls*; they have respective defined 'permeabilities'.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Transfers of energy as work, or as heat, or of matter, between the system and the surroundings, take place through the walls, according to their respective permeabilities.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Matter or energy that pass across the boundary so as to effect a change in the internal energy of the system need to be accounted for in the energy balance equation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The volume contained by the walls can be the region surrounding a single atom resonating energy, such as Max Planck defined in 1900; it can be a body of steam or air in a steam engine, such as Sadi Carnot defined in 1824.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The system could also be just one nuclide (i.e. a system of quarks) as hypothesized in quantum thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] When a looser viewpoint is adopted, and the requirement of thermodynamic equilibrium is dropped, the system can be the body of a tropical cyclone, such as Kerry Emanuel theorized in 1986 in the field of atmospheric thermodynamics, or the event horizon of a black hole.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Boundaries are of four types: fixed, movable, real, and imaginary.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] For example, in an engine, a fixed boundary means the piston is locked at its position, within which a constant volume process might occur.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] If the piston is allowed to move that boundary is movable while the cylinder and cylinder head boundaries are fixed.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] For closed systems, boundaries are real while for open systems boundaries are often imaginary.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In the case of a jet engine, a fixed imaginary boundary might be assumed at the intake of the engine, fixed boundaries along the surface of the case and a second fixed imaginary boundary across the exhaust nozzle.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] As time passes in an isolated system, internal differences of pressures, densities, and temperatures tend to even out.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A system in which all equalizing processes have gone to completion is said to be in a state of thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Once in thermodynamic equilibrium, a system's properties are, by definition, unchanging in time.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Systems in equilibrium are much simpler and easier to understand than are systems which are not in equilibrium.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] When a system is at equilibrium under a given set of conditions, it is said to be in a definite thermodynamic state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The state of the system can be described by a number of state quantities that do not depend on the process by which the system arrived at its state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] They are called intensive variables or extensive variables according to how they change when the size of the system changes.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The properties of the system can be described by an equation of state which specifies the relationship between these variables.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] State may be thought of as the instantaneous quantitative description of a system with a set number of variables held constant.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A thermodynamic process may be defined as the energetic evolution of a thermodynamic system proceeding from an initial state to a final state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] It can be described by process quantities.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] There are two types of thermodynamic instruments, the meter and the reservoir.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A thermodynamic meter is any device which measures any parameter of a thermodynamic system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In some cases, the thermodynamic parameter is actually defined in terms of an idealized measuring instrument.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] For example, the zeroth law states that if two bodies are in thermal equilibrium with a third body, they are also in thermal equilibrium with each other.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] This principle, as noted by James Maxwell in 1872, asserts that it is possible to measure temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] An idealized thermometer is a sample of an ideal gas at constant pressure.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] From the ideal gas law *pV=nRT*, the volume of such a sample can be used as an indicator of temperature; in this manner it defines temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Although pressure is defined mechanically, a pressure-measuring device, called a barometer may also be constructed from a sample of an ideal gas held at a constant temperature.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A calorimeter is a device which is used to measure and define the internal energy of a system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] A thermodynamic reservoir is a system which is so large that its state parameters are not appreciably altered when it is brought into contact with the system of interest.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] When the reservoir is brought into contact with the system, the system is brought into equilibrium with the reservoir.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] For example, a pressure reservoir is a system at a particular pressure, which imposes that pressure upon the system to which it is mechanically connected.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The Earth's atmosphere is often used as a pressure reservoir.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The ocean can act as temperature reservoir when used to cool power plants.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The central concept of thermodynamics is that of energy, the ability to do work.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] By the First Law, the total energy of a system and its surroundings is conserved.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Energy may be transferred into a system by heating, compression, or addition of matter, and extracted from a system by cooling, expansion, or extraction of matter.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In mechanics, for example, energy transfer equals the product of the force applied to a body and the resulting displacement.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Conjugate variables are pairs of thermodynamic concepts, with the first being akin to a "force" applied to some thermodynamic system, the second being akin to the resulting "displacement", and the product of the two equaling the amount of energy transferred.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Thermodynamic potentials are different quantitative measures of the stored energy in a system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Potentials are used to measure the energy changes in systems as they evolve from an initial state to a final state.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The potential used depends on the constraints of the system, such as constant temperature or pressure.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] For example, the Helmholtz and Gibbs energies are the energies available in a system to do useful work when the temperature and volume or the pressure and temperature are fixed, respectively.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Thermodynamic potentials cannot be measured in laboratories, but can be computed using molecular thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] where T is the temperature, S the entropy, p the pressure, V the volume, $\mu$ the chemical potential, N the number of particles in the system, and i is the count of particles types in the system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Thermodynamic potentials can be derived from the energy balance equation applied to a thermodynamic system.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Other thermodynamic potentials can also be obtained through Legendre transformation.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Axiomatic thermodynamics is a mathematical discipline that aims to describe thermodynamics in terms of rigorous axioms, for example by finding a mathematically rigorous way to express the familiar laws of thermodynamics.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] The first attempt at an axiomatic theory of thermodynamics was Constantin Carathéodory's 1909 work *Investigations on the Foundations of Thermodynamics*, which made use of Pfaffian systems and the concept of adiabatic accessibility, a notion that was introduced by Carathéodory himself.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] In this formulation, thermodynamic concepts such as heat, entropy, and temperature are derived from quantities that are more directly measurable.
[src:response-reactions/thermodynamics] Theories that came after, differed in the sense that they made assumptions regarding thermodynamic processes with arbitrary initial and final states, as opposed to considering only neighboring states.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] He received his doctorate in physics and mathematics from the Université Libre de Bruxelles in 1899, for a thesis entitled *Sur la Théorie des Invariants Intégraux* (*On the Theory of Integral Invariants*).
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] He was professor between 1911 and 1942, at the Université Libre de Bruxelles.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] Initially he continued the work of Henri Poincaré and Élie Cartan.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] From 1914 on, he was influenced by the work of Albert Einstein and was an enthusiastic proponent of the theory of relativity.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] He gained significant reputation in 1923, when he developed his definition of chemical affinity.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] He pointed out a connection between the chemical affinity and the Gibbs free energy.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] He is considered the father of thermodynamics of irreversible processes.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] De Donder's work was later developed further by his doctoral student Ilya Prigogine.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] De Donder was an associate and friend of Albert Einstein.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] He was in 1927, one of the participants of the fifth Solvay Conference on Physics, that took place at the International Solvay Institute for Physics in Belgium.
[src:response-reactions/théophile-de-donder] Additionally, De Donder attended the Solvay Conferences of 1924, 1930, and 1948.
